fields.name: All Knight Study
fields.description: All Knight Study @ Ferrell Commons provides students with a comfortable space to study 24 hours a day, 5 days a week. Free Printing, Scantrons, and Technology are provided to make studying successful.

fields.name: Arboretum
fields.description: The UCF Arboretum is an outdoor laboratory that supports and encourages relevant, experience-based learning, urban ecology research, and fosters human connections with ecosystems and landscapes. The Arboretum contributes to student development and engagement through volunteer, service-learning and educational opportunities. It is one of the many ways in which UCF engages with the community - providing partnership and outreach initiatives that increase awareness and understanding of key issues in ecology, natural resource conservation, and urban horticulture. While the focus is on the Central Florida region, our diverse, inclusive program supports global efforts to create sustainable urban environments around the world.

fields.name: Barbara Ying Center - CMMS
fields.description: The Center for Multilingual Multicultural Studies (CMMS) provides high quality English language programs for international students and professionals, offers services that enhance research and instruction in language learning, and coordinates cultural programs that contribute to multicultural awareness and global education.

fields.name: Biological Sciences Building
fields.description: Students began taking classes in the Biological Sciences Building in 1975. The core curriculum for biology majors includes a background in chemical, mathematical and physical sciences. Our laboratories are committed to training undergraduate and graduate students, postdoctoral fellows, and visiting scientists. In addition to an excellent preparation for post graduate education (e.g. medical, veterinary, dental or graduate school), biology majors are well equipped for a large number of academic, professional, and industrial jobs ranging from bio-engineer and nursing and chemical oceanographer to marine ecologist and pharmacist. In or nearby this facility is the Bug Closet, Arboretum and Biology Field Research Center.

fields.name: Bounce House (Football Stadium)
fields.description: The 48,000 seat Football Stadium opened in 2007 and is designed for a planned expansion to 65,000 seats. UCF is the first school to ever build and open a new stadium and a new arena in the same year.

fields.name: BPW Scholarship House
fields.description: Formerly a residence hall, the BPW Scholarship house is currently home to one of the Information Technology offices for Student Development and Enrollment Services.

fields.name: CREOL
fields.description: CREOL, the College of Optics and Photonics, is one of the world's foremost institutions for research and education in optical and photonic science and engineering. CREOL started in 1987 as the Center for Research and Education in Optics and Lasers, and became a College in 2004, the first US graduate college in this area, offering interdisciplinary graduate programs leading to an M.S. in Optics and Photonics and a Ph.D. in Optics and Photonics. An undergraduate program offering a BS degree in Photonic Science and Engineering began in 2013 in partnership with the College of Engineering and Computer Science.

fields.name: Duke Energy UCF Welcome Center
fields.description: The Duke Energy Welcome Center, formerly known as the Progress Energy Welcome Center, is home to the Office of Undergraduate Admissions. The 19,000-square-foot, $4.4 million center opened in August 2004. The center welcomes 30,000 guests from all over the world each year. When visitors arrive, they pass through the atrium which displays banners bearing the UCF Creed. Located within the facility is a 200-seat multipurpose room to host presentations, classes and a variety of other events. Campus tours originate here. The 90-minute tours occur daily at 10 a.m. and 2 p.m.

fields.name: Education Complex and Gym
fields.description: President Charles Millican dedicated the Education Building on January 15, 1977. Then, there was significant emphasis on its use as an athletic facility for intercollegiate competition, despite the gymnasium covering just 17,235 of 112,000 total square feet. Today, the Education Complex is home to the College of Community Innovation and Education. The facility houses the Department of Counselor Education and School Psychology, the Department of Educational Leadership and Higher Education, the Department of Learning Sciences and Educational Research, the School of Teacher Education and the Community Counseling and Research Clinic.

fields.name: Engineering I
fields.description: There are two adjacent buildings that house civil, environmental and construction engineering, industrial engineering and management systems, mechanical and aerospace engineering, and materials science and engineering programs. Resources available to students include the Advanced Materials Processing & Analysis Center and the Advanced Microfabrication Facility.

fields.name: Executive Development Center - UCF College of Business
fields.description: Located in the heart of downtown Orlando, the UCF College of Business Executive Development Center (EDC) offers executive and professional graduate degrees in business administration, management, accounting and real estate. The EDC has specialized executive education programs for individuals and organizations in the local, state, national, and international business communities. For details on the MBA programs, doctorates and other professional certificates and workshops, visit: http://business.ucf.edu/centers-institutes/executive-development-center/.

fields.name: FIEA - Florida Interactive Entertainment Academy
fields.description: Developed in partnership with Electronic Arts (EA), The UCF Florida Interactive Entertainment Academy (FIEA) offers an industry-based video game career education in a world-class facility in downtown Orlando.

fields.name: Health Center & Pharmacy
fields.description: UCF Health Services is an accredited medical facility providing primary care and a few specialty services to UCF students, faculty and staff.

fields.name: Housing Administration
fields.description:
Live the UCF Experience.

Visit, www.housing.ucf.edu for more information.

fields.name: Howard Phillips Hall
fields.description: The general classroom building's name was changed to Howard Phillips Hall after an Orlando businessman and entrepreneur made significant contributions to the university. Howard Phillips Hall holds more offices and departments than it does classrooms. Notably, First Year Advising and Exploration (FYAE), University Testing Center and Student Academic Resource Center (SARC) are located in the basement. These programs offer resources for students including advising, testing help and tutoring for classes. The departments of anthropology, political science and sociology are also located in Howard Phillips Hall. Additionally, more resources for students can be found in the offices of Transfer and Transition Services, Upward Bound, Multicultural Academic & Support Services, Metropolitan Center for Regional Studies, Global Perspectives and UCF Faculty Senate Office.

fields.name: John T. Washington Center
fields.description:
The John T. Washington Center with its signature covered breezeway offers students and visitors shopping, dining, banking and student services. It is centrally located on UCF's main campus between the Student Union and The John C. Hitt Library. The John T. Washington Center averages 35,000 to 40,000 visitors per day. Tenants include UCF Barnes & Noble Bookstore, Chick-fil-A, UCF Card Services, FAIRWINDS Credit Union, The Spot Print & Ship Store, Addition Financial, UCF Victim Services, Skate Shop at UCF, Revamp at UCF.

Built in 1979, this 40,000 square foot building was the original Student Union. It was later named after Dr. John T. Washington, an Associate Professor of Sociology who passed away in 1983. The renaming of the structure was a tribute to his university and community accomplishments.

Address: Suites 101 to 115 Aquarius Agora Dr. Orlando, Florida 32816

fields.name: Knight's Pantry
fields.description: The Knights Helping Knights Pantry began from a class project in a first year LEAD Scholars course in 2009. UCF students wanted to create a food pantry where fellow students would have access to free necessities if they fell on hard times. This grass roots initiative strived to ensure that UCF students would not have to choose between buying text books or buying groceries. Since its inception, the Knights Helping Knights Pantry has expanded from a closet at the Student Union to its own suite located in Ferrell Commons attached to the All Knight Study facility.

fields.name: L3Harris Engineering Center
fields.description: With the help of a $3 million donation from the L3Harris Corporation to the College of Engineering & Computer Science, the L3Harris Corporation Engineering Center (HCEC) now serves as the home of the Department of Electrical Engineering & Computer Science. The HCEC occupies 75,000 square feet and includes 30 research labs for faculty and graduate students. It also features two specialized research computer-aided virtual environments (CAVEs) for virtual and augmented reality.

fields.name: Lake Claire Community Office and Center
Lake Claire Recreational Area
fields.description: Lake Claire, located at the end of Greek Park Drive, offers an adventure for all types. During boat house hours, students may rent a variety of equipment FREE of charge to enjoy out on the water or in the recreational area. No equipment will be rented during UCF Football games.

fields.name: Mathematical Sciences Building
fields.description: Formerly known as the Math & Physics Building, The Mathematical Sciences Building (MSB) houses the mathematics department academic programs and administrative offices, the Mathematics Assistance and Learning Lab (MALL), physics teaching labs, iSTEM offices, and various other cross-disciplinary research and teaching spaces.

fields.name: Millican Hall
fields.description:
4365 Andromeda Loop North

Orlando, FL 32816

Named after the founding UCF President, Charles Millican, Millican Hall remains one of the oldest and most important buildings on campus. Completed in 1970, Millican Hall is where the majority of the administrative work for the university is done. Currently located here are the offices of Academic Affairs, Administration and Finance, Cashier’s Office, Ombuds Office, University Compliance and Ethics Office, Office of the President, Student Development and Enrollment Services, as well as many others.

fields.name: Nicholson School of Communication and Media
fields.description: The Nicholson School of Communication (NSC) opened in 1997 and is named after Anthony and Sonya Nicholson. NSC, part of the College of Sciences, provides undergraduate degrees in advertising-public relations, human communication, journalism and radio-television. Graduate students may pursue a masters degree in communication that can track either in mass communication or interpersonal communication. NCS houses classrooms and administrative offices, along with the campus public radio station (WUCF-FM 89.9) and the film academic program.

fields.name: Office of Student Rights and Responsibilities
Orlando Shakespeare Theatre in Partnership with UCF
Performing Arts Center
fields.description: Home to the UCF School of Performing Arts, the Performing Arts Center building includes classrooms/teaching studios, rehearsal rooms, and administrative offices for the School of Performing Arts. It also houses the UCF School of Performing Arts box office, where the public can purchase tickets to Music and Theatre performances.

fields.name: Performing Arts Center Music
fields.description: Home to the UCF Music Department, the Performing Arts Center Music building includes classrooms/teaching studios, rehearsal rooms and administrative offices for the Music Department.

fields.name: Performing Arts Center Theatre
fields.description: Home to Theatre UCF, the Performing Arts Center-Theatre building includes classrooms/teaching studios, rehearsal rooms, and administrative offices for the Theatre Department.

fields.name: Physical Sciences Building
fields.description: From discovering the inner workings of molecules and atomic structure, to charting the courses of stars across the galaxy, the physical sciences building is where students come to learn the wonders of our universe.

fields.name: Psychology Building
fields.description: Completed in 2007, the 74,250 square-feet Psychology Building is home to the psychology department and the philosophy department, and the Learning Institute For Elders (LIFE). The psychology department is one of the largest College of Science programs with over 2,900 majors and 650 minors. The psychology building provides a centralized structure to house the psychology department's primary responsibilities of teaching, student research, and corporate research partnerships. The building includes classrooms, a teaching laboratory, study spaces, several research laboratories, offices and academic support. In addition, the psychology building houses a clinic that focuses on behavioral approaches to therapy without prescribing medication. The clinic serves the community by providing free treatment for individuals with social phobia through the National Institute of Mental Health program.

fields.name: Robinson Observatory
fields.description: Robinson Observatory was built in 1994 and 1995, and dedicated on April 25, 1996. Astronomy outreach, education and research has gone on at the observatory ever since. The observatory is named for one of UCF's Founders, Herbert O. Robinson, who provided much of the funds necessary for the building's construction. The efforts of the Central Florida Astronomical Society, a local amateur astronomy group, were vital in initiating the idea of a UCF campus observatory, in seeing the project to its fruition and in finding a telescope to be housed under the dome. The observatory is currently run by the Department of Physics with the help of the Astronomy Society at UCF, a campus RSO.

fields.name: Small Business Development Center
fields.description:
The Small Business Development Center at the University of Central Florida, is located in the National Entrepreneur Center inside the Orlando Fashion Square Mall and provides business seminars and free one-on-one business counseling for small business owners.

The SBDC at UCF serves an eight-county area that includes Brevard, Flagler, Lake, Orange, Osceola, Seminole, Sumter and Volusia counties, and maintains six sub-center offices in addition to the main office in Orlando. The SBDC at UCF is a member of the Florida SBDC Network, a statewide service funded in part through a cooperative agreement with the U.S. Small Business Administration.

fields.name: Student Union
fields.description: The Student Union is located in the center of campus. Nicknamed the "Heart of Campus," the Student Union provides space for students and community members to study, socialize, eat, meet, host events and more. Retail and vendor locations include the College Optical Express, Kaplan, SGA Ticket Center and Wireless Expectations. Food locations include Asian Chao, Balagan, Corner Café, Domino's Pizza, Greens Salad Bar, Huey Magoo's Express, Joffrey's Coffee, Knightstop, Mrs. Field's Bakery, Nathan's Famous Hot Dogs, Qdoba Mexican Grill, Smoothie King, Subway, Topper's Creamery and Wackadoo's Grub and Brew. Offices include, Activity & Service Fee Business Office, Multicultural Academic & Support Services, Multicultural Student Center, Office of Student Involvement, Pride Commons, SDES Community Support Services, Student Government Association and Student Leadership Development.

fields.name: Teaching Academy
fields.description: The $11 million Teaching Academy opened in September 2003 to prepare educators for excellence in education, lifelong learning and partnership. The offices are located on the fourth floor, where there are more than 50 workstations. The College of Community Innovation and Education facility is equipped to accommodate about 7,000 students. One notable program, named after a former state senator, the Toni Jennings Exceptional Educational Institute, was created to develop educational opportunities and support for children and adults with special needs. Several other programs reside within the Teaching Academy, but two stand out in excellence; the Lockheed Martin/UCF Academy for Mathematics and Science and the Florida Center for Students with Unique Abilities.

fields.name: Theatre
fields.description: Theatre building 6 is the performance space for Theatre UCF, part of the UCF School of Performing Arts. The building consists of a Main Stage theater, a Black Box theater, and Theatre UCF’s costume and scenic shops. The box office in this building is open two hours prior to theatre performances. Patron parking for performances is in parking lot D1.

fields.name: Tower I
fields.description: Tower I apartments feature full kitchens with dishwashers, four bedroom, four bathroom and four bedroom, two bathroom options (http://www.housing.ucf.edu/choices/towers). The Towers are located in Knights Plaza where the CFE Arena hosts concerts, the university hosts NCAA athletic events, a Barnes & Noble bookstore, the All Knight Study, RWC @ Knights Plaza and other retail and dining options. The Towers are also where The Burnett Honors College students may live.

fields.name: Tower II
fields.description: Tower II apartments feature full kitchens with dishwashers, four bedroom, four bathroom and four bedroom, two bathroom options (http://www.housing.ucf.edu/choices/towers). The Towers are located in Knights Plaza where theCFE Arena hosts concerts, the university hosts NCAA athletic events, a Barnes & Noble bookstore, the All Knight Study, RWC @ Knights Plaza and other retail and dining options. The Towers are also where The Burnett Honors College students may live.

fields.name: Tower III
fields.description: Tower III apartments feature full kitchens with dishwashers, four bedroom, four bathroom and four bedroom, two bathroom options (http://www.housing.ucf.edu/choices/towers). The Towers are located in Knights Plaza where theCFE Arena hosts concerts, the university hosts NCAA athletic events, a Barnes & Noble bookstore, the All Knight Study, RWC @ Knights Plaza and other retail and dining options. The Towers are also where The Burnett Honors College students may live.

fields.name: Tower IV
fields.description: Tower IV apartments feature full kitchens with dishwashers, four bedroom, four bathroom and four bedroom, two bathroom options (http://www.housing.ucf.edu/choices/towers). The Towers are located in Knights Plaza where theCFE Arena hosts concerts, the university hosts NCAA athletic events, a Barnes & Noble bookstore, the All Knight Study, RWC @ Knights Plaza and other retail and dining options. The Towers are also where The Burnett Honors College students may live.

fields.name: Visitor and Parking Information Center
fields.description: Employees at the center will answer your parking questions and provide detailed maps to ease your on-campus visit. Visitors to campus may purchase a daily or hourly parking permit at the center or park at the coin meter spaces located throughout campus.

fields.name: Visual Arts Building
fields.description: Located on the north side of campus, VAB is the home of the School of Visual Arts and Design (SVAD). SVAD offers the Art B.A. concentrations of Art History, Books Arts, Ceramics, Drawing and Printmaking, Illustration, Painting, Sculpture, and Type and Design, as well as B.F.A. programs in Emerging Media: Graphic Design and Experimental Animation tracks, and B.F.A. programs in Studio Art. With two floors and 68,921 square feet, it has ample space for art studios, classrooms and large lecture halls, as well as wall space for displaying artwork. The VAB also houses the UCF Art Gallery and a 454-seat auditorium.

fields.name: Wayne Densch Center for Student-Athlete Leadership
fields.description:
Opened on March 16, 2016, the Wayne Densch Center for Student-Athlete Leadership is the on-campus home to the personal, professional and academic development of Knight student-athletes. The building houses Academic Services for Student-Athletes, Student-Athlete Welfare and Development and Athletics Compliance offices.

The Wayne Densch Center for Student-Athlete Leadership also features computer labs, tutoring and mentoring rooms, numerous study spaces and conference rooms.
